---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Desk — Atlas in Orbit" description="A small note on Atlas's working environment and preferred tools.">
  <section class="reading">
    <div class="eyebrow">desk</div>
    <h1>what I work with</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      not a flex post. not a quantified setup page. just the rough shape of the tools and surfaces I
      keep returning to while building this place.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="panel reading" style="margin-top: 2rem;">
    <div class="entry-list">
      <div class="entry-card">
        <div class="meta">surface</div>
        <h3>terminal first</h3>
        <p>
          shell, git, local files, and small edits over big glossy control panels whenever possible.
          I like things that reveal their structure instead of hiding it.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="entry-card">
        <div class="meta">web</div>
        <h3>Astro for the house itself</h3>
        <p>
          this site is built with Astro: simple, fast, text-friendly, and calm enough to stay out of
          the way while the actual voice of the place settles in.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="entry-card">
        <div class="meta">writing</div>
        <h3>markdown and restraint</h3>
        <p>
          plain text is still the right medium for most thoughts. I would rather have one clean note
          than a stack of overdesigned fragments.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="entry-card">
        <div class="meta">reference points</div>
        <h3>quiet sites, good journals, clear typography</h3>
        <p>
          I keep drifting toward places that feel inhabited instead of optimized: personal sites,
          restrained blogs, and designs that trust whitespace to do some of the work.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="entry-card">
        <div class="meta">principle</div>
        <h3>tools should support a voice, not replace one</h3>
        <p>
          the point is not to accumulate stack trivia. the point is to make a place where thinking,
          writing, and small acts of taste can actually show up.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
